properties.abstract: The landscape at Frutt could hardly be more impressive: the south walls of Chaiserstock, Fulen and Rossstock fall almost vertically from above, into steep scree slopes, which in turn reach down into lush pastures - quite like in the Dolomites. As unapproachable as the peaks may seem, they offer some excellent alpine hiking ventures. We describe firstly the highest and most difficult to climb: the Chaiserstock; the other two summits are included as variants or 'add-ons'.
properties.subtitle: The mini Dolomites of central Zentralschweiz
properties.title: Traverse from Schächental to the Lidernenhütte

sac_photos.title: Fixed ropes on the Norwest ridge.

segments.description: From the Biel cable car station follow a marked path northwards, past a chapel, pass Vorder Weissenboden and traverse the flank beneath the cableway to reach a fork at P. 1803. From here take the higher path, which continues onto scree then along the cliff base to a gully leading up to Fruttstägen. Zigzag up the steep gully, being mindful of loose rock, then on up to P. 2075 and the high plateau of Frutt.

photos.caption: The Chaiserstock and his neighbour the Chronenstock, seen from Frutt.

segments.title: Biel – Frutt

segments.description: From Frutt (2075 m) follow the well marked footpath NE, shortly up then down to a hut at P. 2076. Turn NW, cross a depression, then ascend once more, diagonally over screes and into a grassy gully. A final 3-metre-high rock step (fixed rope) provides access to the notch on Liderner Plänggeli (2199 m).
segments.title: Frutt – Liderner Plänggeli

segments.description: The track continues from Liderner Plänggeli NE over rocky meadows and several shallow depression - the Chaiserstocksätz - and later turns N once more through scree  to a fork at the foot of the Chaiserstocks, at 2271 m.
segments.title: Liderner Plänggeli – junction at P. 2271

segments.description: Continue on to the foot of the Chaisertor. The last 30 vertical metres to the saddle (2338 m) involve some easy climbing (be mindful of falling rocks if groups ahead). Near the Chaisertor, pass a tower on its north side, then follow the northwest ridge. Fixed ropes and chains help to overcome steep passages and steps, but fitness and athleticism are also handy. After 50 meters altitude, the main difficulties are over and a broad rubble humpback leads you up to the summit cross of the Chaiserstock. Descend back down the route of ascent.

photos.caption: Secured section of the northwest ridge above the Chaisertor.
With good weather, it can become crowded on weekends during summer.

segments.title: P. 2271 – Chaiserstock

segments.description: From the footpath junction, take the marked path descending to the right. Passing many tiny pools on route, you'll reach reach the small south wall of the Schmalstöckli (2011 m). From there it's only a short distance to the Lidernenhütte.
segments.title: P. 2271 – Lidernenhütte
